5′-end SAGE for the analysis of transcriptional start sites |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_largest0 xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Shin-ichi Hashimoto1, Yutaka Suzuki2,4, Yasuhiro Kasai3,4, Kei Morohoshi1, Tomoyuki Yamada3, Jun Sese3, |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_largest-2 xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Shinichi Morishita3, Sumio Sugano2 & Kouji Matsushima1 |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_largest-2 xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Identification of the mRNA start site is essential in establish- |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
ing the full-length cDNA sequence of a gene and analyzing its |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
promoter region, which regulates gene expression. Here we |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
describe the development of a 5′-end serial analysis of gene |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
expression (5′ SAGE) that can be used to globally identify |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
transcriptional start sites and the frequency of individual |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
mRNAs. Of the 25,684 5′ SAGE tags in the HEK293 human |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
cell library, 19,893 matched to the human genome. Among |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
15,448 tags in one locus of the genome, 85.8%–96.1% of the |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
5′ SAGE tags were assigned within –500 to +200 nt of mRNA |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
start sites using the RefSeq, UniGene and DBTSS databases. |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
This technique should facilitate 5′-end transcriptome analysis |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
in a variety of cells and tissues. |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
Comprehensive analysis of gene expression in different cell sub- |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
populations and microanatomic structures provides insight into |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
human development and physiology. Recently developed functional |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
genomic technologies such as cDNA microarrays1 and serial analysis of |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
gene expression (SAGE)2 allow for the analysis of the expression of |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
thousands of genes. The SAGE method has proved to be a useful tool |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
for quantifying, cataloging and comparing the expression of genes in |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
cells and tissues that are in various physiological, developmental and |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
pathological states3–5. |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
In the human genome project6, genes were predicted based on infor- |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
mation obtained from expressed sequence tag (EST) maps, analysis of |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
full-length cDNAs and computational annotation by Genscan, Genie, |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
FGENES and other programs. However, these computational analyses |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
had limitations. For example, they were unable to provide definitive |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
evidence that a hypothetical gene was actually expressed. The Long |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
SAGE method is useful in rapidly identifying not only novel genes and |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
exons but also the frequency of each transcript. However, a remaining |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
challenge in human genome expression profile analysis is the exact iden- |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
tification and annotation of entire expressed genes based on informa- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
tion concerning their 5′ -end to 3′ -end transcripts. Therefore, a method |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
for precisely and globally identifying the 5′ ends of transcripts is needed. |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Such a 5′-end capping method7 would give us the sequence tag to the |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
first base of an mRNA. Using cDNA libraries made from oligo-capped |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
mRNA preparations and SAGE, we developed a method to comprehen- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
sively identify the transcriptional start sites of mRNAs. |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
The method is shown in Figure 1. The mRNA is split into two ali- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
quots and its cap structure is enzymatically replaced with two types of |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
synthetic oligonucleotides containing MmeI, a type-IIS restriction |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
endonuclease site, and the XhoI restriction enzyme site. Oligo- |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
capping mRNA is then converted into first strand cDNA with a random |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
adapter-primer. The second strand is synthesized using biotin-bound |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
5′-primer and random adaptor-primer by PCR. The double-stranded |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
cDNA is then cleaved with MmeI, which cleaves 20 bp away from its |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
recognition site. After the 5′ -cDNAs are isolated by binding to strepta- |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
vidin beads, the two pools of tags are ligated to each other. The subse- |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
quent procedure for concatemerization is carried out according to the |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
original SAGE protocol2. |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Using this method, we characterized 25,684 transcripts expressed |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
in HEK293 cells as a test cell line and compared them to the human |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
genome sequence. A total of 19,893 tags matched perfectly to genomic |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
sequences representing 13,404 different tags (Table 1). Eighty percent |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
(10,706 tags) of 13,404 different tags were assigned to unique posi- |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
tions. Eleven percent (1,483 tags) of the tags matched two loci in the |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
genome, 8.1% (1,090 tags) matched 3–99 loci, and 0.9% (125 tags) |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
matched >100 loci. The tags that mapped to multiple genomic loci |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
mostly corresponded to retrotransposon elements, repetitive sequences, |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
or pseudogenes. |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
We estimated whether the 5′ SAGE tags matched to the mRNA |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
start sites using three databases: the reference sequence database |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
(RefSeq), the Gene Resource Locator (GRL) database, which assembles |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
gene maps that include information on cis-elements in regulatory |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
regions and alternatively spliced transcripts, and the database of |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Transcriptional Start Sites (DBTSS)8, which contains systematic 5′-end |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
sequences of human full-length cDNAs. The distance distributions and |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
the number and ratio of small-distance tag occurrences that we |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
obtained are shown in Figure 2a and Table 2. The data indicate that our |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
5′ SAGE tags coincided well with start site information for each data- |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
base. Most (85.8%–98.2%) tags that mapped to each database were |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
–500 to +200 nt of mRNA start sites. Notably, 23.5%–49.3% of 5′ SAGE |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
tags hit the upstream regions of the defined transcription start sites |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
(TSS) in these databases. |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
To experimentally confirm the 5′ ends of known genes identified by |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
5′ SAGE, we compared the directed sequencing data of the 5′ ends of |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
captured full-length cDNAs in HEK293 with 5′ SAGE data. The repre- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
sentative TSS identified by 5′ SAGE and full-length cDNA using the |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
oligo-capping method are shown in Supplementary Figure 1. A part of |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
various 5′ SAGE tags corresponded to those of full-length cDNA using |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
the oligo-capping method. |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
