Several groups reported that mRNA start sites9 and polyadenylation |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
cleavage sites10 show heterogeneity. Although TSS differences have been |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
reported for specific genes in tissues1 1, our data showed that the diver- |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
sity of TSS already exists on a cellular level. Moreover, our data pro- |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
vide direct evidence of heterogeneity of TSS and 3′ end regions using |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
5′ SAGE and 3′ SAGE methods. For example, we found that the peroxi- |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
some proliferator-activated receptor–binding protein has one TSS and |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
two 3′ SAGE tag sites, ribosomal protein S4 has 16 TSS and one 3′ SAGE |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
tag site, and calreticulin has seven TSS and one 3′ SAGE tag site. |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Alternative mRNA splicing contributes in important ways to the |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
complexity of the human proteome. Recent genomic studies suggest |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
that 40%–60% of human genes are alternatively spliced 12. Fifteen |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
percent of point mutations are estimated to cause human genetic dis- |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
eases by triggering an mRNA splicing defect13. It has been reported that |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
49% of the transcriptional units with multiple splice forms included |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
transcripts in which usage of an alternative TSS was accompanied by |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
alternative splicing of the initial exon14. We also found that the mRNA |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
start sites of several genes, such as peroxiredoxin 4(NM_006406), repre- |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
sented not only different splicing variants of mRNA but also different |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
degrees of gene expression, suggesting that alternative transcription may |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
frequently induce alternative splicing. |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
In conclusion, our 5′ SAGE method should facilitate the annotation |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
of genomes. Because this method represents one of the few high- |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
throughput discovery approaches that does not depend on a priori |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
knowledge of gene sequences, it can be used for independent valida- |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
tion of in silico gene predictions and for the identification of nonanno- |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
tated regions. In addition, it should be useful for finding single |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
nucleotide polymorphisms in 5′-untranslated or promoter regions. |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Considering the diversity of 5′ ends, it is more appropriate to perform |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
5′ SAGE rather than 3′ SAGE when determining the frequency of gene |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
expression. Comprehensive identification of genes transcribed from |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
specific mRNA start sites in different cell types will not only provide |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
insight into the functional complexity of the human genome but may |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
also aid the diagnosis of various disorders such as cancer and immuno- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
logical and neural diseases. |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
METHODS |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Generation of 3′-Long SAGE library. Total RNA was prepared from HEK239 cells |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
and mRNA was isolated as previously described15. Long SAGE was performed as |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
previously described2. SAGE 2000 software (version 4.12) was used to quantify |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
the abundance of each tag. After elimination of the linker sequences, other poten- |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
tial artifacts and repeated ditags, each tag was analyzed. |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Generation of 5′ SAGE library. Oligo-capping was done as described by |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Maruyama and Sugano7 with some modifications16. Briefly, 5–10 g of poly(A)+ |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
1148	VOLUME 22 NUMBER 9 SEPTEMBER 2004 NATURE BIOTECHNOLOGY |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
LETTERS |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_largest-1 xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
RNA were treated with 1.2 units of bacterial alkaline phosphatase (BAP; TaKaRa) |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
in 100 l of 100 mM Tris-HCl (pH 8.0) containing 5 mM 2-mercaptoethanol and |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
100 units of RNAsin (Promega) at 37 °C for 40 min. After extraction twice with |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
phenol:chloroform (1:1) and ethanol precipitation, the poly(A)+ RNA was |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
treated with 20 units of tobacco acid pyrophosphatase (TAP) in 100 l of 50 mM |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
sodium acetate (pH 5.5), 1 mM EDTA, 5 mM 2-mercaptoethanol and 100 units |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
of RNAsin at 37 °C for 45 min. After phenol:chloroform extraction and ethanol |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
precipitation, 2–4 g of the BAP-TAP-treated poly(A)+ RNA were divided into |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
two pools, and one of the following RNA linkers containing recognition sites for |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
XhoI/MmeI was ligated to each pool—5′ -oligo 1 (5′-UUU GGA UUU GCU GGU |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
GCA GUA CAA CUA GGC UUA AUA CUC GAG UCC GACG -3′) or 5′ -oligo 2 |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
(5′-UUU CTG CUC GAA UUC AAG CUU CUA ACG AUG UAC GCU CGA |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
GUC CGA CG -3′)—using 250 units of RNA ligase (TaKaRa) in 100 ml of 50 mM |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Tris-HCl (pH 7.5), 5 mM MgCl2, 5 mM 2-mercaptoethanol, 0.5 mM ATP, |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
25% PEG8000 and 100 units of RNAsin at 20 °C for 3–16 h. |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
After removing unligated 5′-oligo, cDNA was synthesized with RNaseH-free |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
reverse-transcriptase (Superscript II, Gibco BRL). For the 5′-end-enriched cDNA |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
library, 10 pmol of random adapter-primer (5′-GCG GCT GAA GAC GGC CTA |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
TGT GGC CNN N NC-3′) was used and incubation was carried out at 12 °C for |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
1 h and 42 °C for another hour. |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
After first-strand synthesis, RNA was degraded in 15 mM NaOH at 65 °C for |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
1 h. The cDNA that was made from 10 g of oligo-capped poly(A)+ RNA was |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
amplified in a volume of 100 l using an XL PCR kit (Perkin-Elmer) with |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
16 pmol of 5′ (5′ biotin- GGA TTT GCT GGT GCA GTA CAA CTA GGC TTA |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
ATA-3′ or 5′ biotin- CTG CTC GAA TTC AAG CTT CTA ACG ATG TAC G-3′) |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
and 3′ (5′-GCG GCT GAA GAC GGC CTA TGT-3′) PCR primers. Random |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
adapter-primer-primed cDNA was amplified for 10 cycles at 94 °C for 1 min, |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
58 °C for 1 min and 72 °C for 2 min. PCR products were extracted with |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
phenol:chloroform (1:1) once, ethanol-precipitated and digested with the MmeI |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
type-IIS restriction endonuclease (University of Gdansk Center for Technology |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Transfer). Digestion was performed at 37 °C for 2.5 h using 40 units MmeI in |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
300 l of 10 mM HEPES, pH 8.0, 2.5 mM potassium acetate, 5 mM magnesium |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
acetate, 2 mM DTT and 40 M S-adenosylmethionine. The digested 5′-terminal |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
cDNA fragments were bound to streptavidin-coated magnetic beads (Dynal). |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
cDNA fragments that bound to the beads were directly ligated together in 16 l of |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
reaction mixture containing four units of T4 DNA ligase in the supplied buffer |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
for 2.5 h at 16 °C. The ditags were amplified by PCR using primers 5′ -GGA TTT |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
GCT GGT GCA GTA CAA CTA GGC-3′ and 5′-CTG CTC GAA TTC AAG CTT |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
CTA ACG ATG-3′. The PCR products were analyzed by PAGE and digested with |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
XhoI. The band containing the ditags was excised and self-ligated to produce long |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
concatemers which were then cloned into the XhoI site of pZero 1.0 (Invitrogen). |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Colonies were screened with PCR using M13 forward and reverse primers. PCR |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
products containing inserts of more than 600 bp were sequenced with the Big |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Dye terminator ver.3 and analyzed using a 3730 ABI automated DNA sequencer |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
(Applied Biosystems). All electropherograms were reanalyzed by visual inspec- |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
tion to check for ambiguous bases and to correct misreads. SAGE 2000 software |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
(version 4.12) was used to quantify the abundance of each tag. In this study, we |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
obtained 18–19 bp tag information. 5′ SAGE and 3′ SAGE data are available at |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
http://sage.gi.k.u-tokyo.ac.jp/. |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Generation of captured full-length cDNA library. The captured full-length |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
cDNA library in HEL293 was constructed using the oligo-capping method as |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_continue
described before16. The 5′ ends of 7,903 clones sequenced were analyzed as well as |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
5′ SAGE tags. The raw sequencing data are deposited in DDBJ and are also avail- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
able as a Supplementary Note online and at http://sage.gi.k.u-tokyo.ac.jp/. |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Association of 5′ SAGE tag with corresponding genes. To assess the validity of |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
5′ SAGE tags for identifying transcriptional start sites, we avoided aligning |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_continue
5′ SAGE tags (18 bp) with the current cDNA/EST database because the sequences |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
were not always read from their transcriptional start sites. We instead attempted |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
to align our 5′-tags with the human genome sequence, the NCBI build 34 avail- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
able from http://genome.ucsc.edu/, by using the alignment program ALPS that is |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
publicly available from http://alps.gi.k.u-tokyo.ac.jp/. Only tags that matched in |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
the sense orientation were considered for this analysis. |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
The regions adjacent to the alignment location of each 5′-tag were searched to |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
find their corresponding transcript by using the Gene Resource Locator data- |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
base17, a database of sequence alignments from various resources such as |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
UniGene (Build 162)18. A major problem that we ran into was that, owing to |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
retro-transposition and genome-duplication, one 5′-tag could be aligned with |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
multiple locations, though many of these were noncoding regions. The issue was |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
resolved by selecting gene-coding locations that were annotated in the UniGene |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
database. Although 3′ -tags often fell in the 3′-end exons, 5′-tags did not necessar- |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
ily hit the first exons. Thus the search was made within 500 bp from the alignment |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
position of each 5′-tag. |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
Consistency with known 5′ transcriptional start sites. A small distance between |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
the aligned positions of each 5′ SAGE tag and its corresponding gene implied that |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_continue
the 5′ tag was nearly consistent with the known 5′ transcriptional start site.To cal- |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
culate the distance, however, we had to bear in mind that, near the 5′ tag, multiple |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
cDNA/EST sequence alignments might be observed because of alternative splic- |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
ing. To resolve this problem and assign a unique value to the distance, we selected |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
the alignment that was closest to the 5′ tag. The distance was defined as being neg- |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
ative if the 5′ tag was located in the upstream region of its corresponding cDNA. |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Otherwise, the value was deemed positive or zero; the zero distance indicated the |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
perfect coincidence. To observe the overall distance distribution, we calculated |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
the total number of 5′ SAGE tag occurrences between –500 to +200 nt of the |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
mRNA start sites. We used RefSeq, UniGene(GRL) and DBTSS databases sepa- |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
rately to determine differences in their coverage of the transcriptional start sites. |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Note: Supplementary information is available on the Nature Biotechnology website. |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_yes xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
